('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:8383ff7e', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘De todos los coches, ___ más me gusta es éste.’ (the one that)", "options": ["el que", "el cual", "lo que", "el mío"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘el que’ refers back to ‘el coche’ already understood from context. ‘el cual’ is more formal, ‘lo que’ refers to an idea rather than one noun, and ‘el mío’ means ‘mine’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:90ba497a', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘Estudio mucho ___ aprender español.’ (in order to)", "options": ["para", "por", "sin", "desde"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘para + infinitive’ expresses purpose (in order to). ‘por’ often gives a reason/cause instead, ‘sin’ means without, and ‘desde’ means since/from."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:04d32e33', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "How do you say ‘another day’ correctly in Spanish?", "options": ["otro día", "un otro día", "otro día más", "el otro día"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Spanish never puts ‘un’ before ‘otro’ (never ‘un otro día’). ‘el otro día’ means ‘the other day’ (a different meaning), and ‘otro día más’ adds an unnecessary ‘more’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:a8f139bb', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘¿Vas a ir ___ día a España?’ (some day)", "options": ["algún", "alguno", "ninguno", "otro"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘alguno’ shortens to ‘algún’ before a masculine singular noun like ‘día’. ‘ninguno’ means ‘no/not any’ (opposite meaning), and ‘otro’ means ‘another’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:2bd66818', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘Llegó ___ decir nada.’ (without saying anything)", "options": ["sin", "con", "desde", "hasta"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘sin + infinitive’ = without doing something. ‘con’ means with, ‘desde’ means since/from, and ‘hasta’ means until."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:30eb0ebd', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘Trabajé ___ las diez de la noche.’ (until)", "options": ["hasta", "desde", "para", "sin"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘hasta’ = until/up to a point in time. ‘desde’ means since/from (the opposite direction), ‘para’ means for/in order to, and ‘sin’ means without."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:32fc6049', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘Vuestro coche es azul; ___ es rojo.’ (ours)", "options": ["el nuestro", "el vuestro", "el suyo", "el mío"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘el nuestro’ = ours, matching ‘coche’ (masc.). ‘el vuestro’ would repeat ‘yours’, ‘el suyo’ = his/hers/theirs, and ‘el mío’ = mine."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:1f967bf8', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which word means ‘that (over there)’, far from both speaker and listener?", "options": ["aquel", "aquellos", "esos", "estos"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘aquel’ = that (over there), far from both people. ‘aquellos’ is the plural form of the same word, ‘esos’ = those (middle distance), and ‘estos’ = these (close)."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:aa729ee4', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘No quiero té, ___ café.’ (but rather)", "options": ["sino", "pero", "aunque", "además"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "After a negative, use ‘sino’ (not ‘pero’) to contrast two things directly. ‘aunque’ means although, and ‘además’ means furthermore."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:919af4d7', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘La empresa para ___ trabajo es española.’ (which — formal, after a preposition)", "options": ["la cual", "que", "quienes", "la que"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "After a preposition, formal Spanish prefers ‘la cual’, agreeing with ‘la empresa’. Bare ‘que’ sounds too casual here, ‘quienes’ is plural and for people, and ‘la que’ is also possible but less common in this formal register."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:277f1ce7', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘¿___ cuesta el billete?’ (how much)", "options": ["cuánto", "cuántos", "cuántas", "cuánta"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘cuánto’ is the default (uninflected) form asking about an amount/price. ‘cuántos/cuántas’ agree with a plural noun, and ‘cuánta’ is feminine singular — none fit here since there''s no noun to agree with."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:df82f516', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘Tu libro está aquí; ¿dónde está ___?’ (mine)", "options": ["el mío", "el tuyo", "el suyo", "el nuestro"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘el mío’ = mine. ‘el tuyo’ = yours, ‘el suyo’ = his/hers/theirs, and ‘el nuestro’ = ours."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:b04d59e3', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "How do you write 21 correctly in Spanish (one word)?", "options": ["veintiuno", "veinte y uno", "veinte uno", "veintiúno"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "21 is written as one word: veintiuno. Writing it as three separate words (‘veinte y uno’) is the old-fashioned style, and ‘veinte uno’ is missing the ‘y’ entirely."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:d529b2f2', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Complete: ‘¿Tienes hermanos? No, no tengo ___.’ (any/none)", "options": ["ninguno", "algunos", "otro más", "todos ellos"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘ninguno’ = none/not any, matching a previously mentioned masc. noun (hermanos). ‘algunos’ = some, ‘otro más’ = one more/another, and ‘todos ellos’ = all of them — the opposite meaning."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:mcq:780fe27a', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "How do you say ‘a million euros’ correctly?", "options": ["un millón de euros", "cien mil euros exactos", "un millón euros", "mil euros solamente"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘un millón’ needs ‘de’ before the noun: un millón de euros. Omitting ‘de’ (option 3) is a common mistake. ‘cien mil’ means 100,000, and ‘mil euros solamente’ just means ‘a thousand euros only’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:e9c5a8d1', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Spanish usually drops subject pronouns like ‘yo’ and ‘tú’ because the verb ending shows who is speaking."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Hablo español needs no ‘yo’ — the -o ending already shows it."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:5214ceb5', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘lo’ and ‘la’ are indirect object pronouns."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "‘lo’ and ‘la’ are DIRECT object pronouns; ‘le’ and ‘les’ are indirect."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:709f35de', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A direct object pronoun can attach to the end of an infinitive, e.g. ‘voy a verlo’."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "voy a verlo = I''m going to watch it, with ‘lo’ attached to the infinitive."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:086284b4', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Reflexive pronouns are only used in the plural."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Reflexive pronouns exist for every person: me, te, se, nos, os, se."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:95b4f2aa', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘que’ can refer to both people and things."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "El chico que vive aquí… / El libro que compré… — que works for both."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:db42cc4f', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘lo que’ means ‘the’ and goes before every noun."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "‘lo que’ means ‘what/that which’ and refers to a whole idea, not a single noun."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:b88514d8', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Spanish uses a double negative, e.g. ‘no veo nada’."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "‘no’ plus a negative word (nada, nunca, nadie…) is the normal Spanish pattern."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:64e249d0', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘sin embargo’ and ‘aunque’ are examples of negatives."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "They are CONNECTORS (however / although), not negatives."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:1c2e380a', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘otro’ can be preceded by ‘un/una’ in Spanish, e.g. ‘un otro día’."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Spanish never uses ‘un/una’ before ‘otro’ — just ‘otro día’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:c33a302a', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘alguno’ shortens to ‘algún’ before a masculine singular noun."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "algún día, algún amigo — the final -o drops before a masc. singular noun."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:1558655d', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘estos’ and ‘esos’ show exactly the same distance from the speaker."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "‘estos’ = close to the speaker (these); ‘esos’ = a bit further away (those)."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:02c5f5d0', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘contigo’ is written as two separate words: ‘con tigo’."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "‘contigo’ is always one word — it''s an irregular contraction of con + ti."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:5147b6f2', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Hundreds like ‘setecientos’ and ‘novecientos’ change to agree with a feminine noun."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "setecientas personas, novecientas páginas — hundreds (200+) agree in gender, unlike smaller numbers."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:1589b189', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘mil’ can be written with ‘un’ in front of it, like English ‘a thousand’ → ‘un mil’."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Spanish just says ‘mil’ on its own — never ‘un mil’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tf:da4c2718', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘sino’ is used instead of ‘pero’ after a negative, to contrast two things directly."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "No es rojo, sino azul — ‘sino’ replaces ‘pero’ after ‘no’ when directly contrasting."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:bf3278c8', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "When do I use (or drop) subject pronouns?", "reading": "<p>Subject pronouns are <span data-say=\"yo\">yo</span> (I), <span data-say=\"tú\">tú</span> (you), <span data-say=\"él\">él</span> / <span data-say=\"ella\">ella</span> (he/she), <span data-say=\"nosotros\">nosotros / nosotras</span> (we), <span data-say=\"vosotros\">vosotros / vosotras</span> (you all) and <span data-say=\"ellos\">ellos</span> / <span data-say=\"ellas\">ellas</span> (they).</p>\n            <p>Spanish verb endings already show <em>who</em> is doing the action, so subject pronouns are usually <strong>dropped</strong>: <span data-say=\"Hablo español.\">Hablo español.</span> (I speak Spanish) needs no ‘yo’.</p>\n            <p>Keep the pronoun only for <strong>emphasis or contrast</strong>: <span data-say=\"Yo prefiero el fútbol, pero él prefiere el baloncesto.\">Yo prefiero el fútbol, pero él prefiere el baloncesto.</span> — <em>I prefer football, but he prefers basketball.</em></p>", "question": "Why does Spanish often drop ‘yo’, ‘tú’, etc.?", "options": ["the verb ending already shows who is doing the action", "subject pronouns are considered rude in spoken Spanish", "subject pronouns only exist for plural forms", "Spanish sentences never contain a conjugated verb"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The verb ending (hablo, hablas, habla…) already tells you the subject, so the pronoun is optional unless you need emphasis or contrast."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:459b64a0', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Direct object pronouns: lo, la, los, las", "reading": "<p>Use a <strong>direct object pronoun</strong> to avoid repeating a noun you have just mentioned: <span data-say=\"lo\">lo</span> (him/it, masc.), <span data-say=\"la\">la</span> (her/it, fem.), <span data-say=\"los\">los</span> (them, masc.), <span data-say=\"las\">las</span> (them, fem.).</p>\n            <p>Position: put it <strong>before a conjugated verb</strong> — <span data-say=\"¿Tienes el libro?\">¿Tienes el libro?</span> <span data-say=\"Sí, lo tengo.\">Sí, lo tengo.</span> (Yes, I have it) — or <strong>attach it to an infinitive</strong>: <span data-say=\"Voy a verlo.\">Voy a verlo.</span> (I’m going to watch it).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"lo veo\">lo veo</span></td><td>I see him / it (masc.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"la veo\">la veo</span></td><td>I see her / it (fem.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"los veo\">los veo</span></td><td>I see them (masc.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"las veo\">las veo</span></td><td>I see them (fem.)</td></tr>\n            </table>", "question": "Where does the direct object pronoun ‘lo’ go with a conjugated verb like ‘veo’?", "options": ["before the verb: lo veo", "after the verb with a gap: veo lo", "attached to the end of the conjugated verb: veolo", "it can never be used with a conjugated verb"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "With a conjugated verb the pronoun goes immediately before it: lo veo. It only attaches to the END of an infinitive or gerund."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:e7578967', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Indirect object and reflexive pronouns", "reading": "<p><strong>Indirect object pronouns</strong> (to/for whom) are <span data-say=\"me\">me</span>, <span data-say=\"te\">te</span>, <span data-say=\"le\">le</span>, <span data-say=\"nos\">nos</span>: <span data-say=\"Le doy el regalo a mi madre.\">Le doy el regalo a mi madre.</span> (I give the present to my mother.)</p>\n            <p><strong>Reflexive pronouns</strong> (me, te, se, nos, os, se) show the action is done <em>to yourself</em>: <span data-say=\"me levanto\">me levanto</span> (I get up), <span data-say=\"se levanta\">se levanta</span> (he/she gets up).</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> When a direct AND indirect pronoun combine, ‘le’/‘les’ change to <strong>se</strong>: <span data-say=\"Se lo doy a mi hermano.\">Se lo doy a mi hermano.</span> — <em>I give it to my brother.</em></p>", "question": "Which set of pronouns is used for reflexive verbs like ‘levantarse’?", "options": ["me, te, se, nos, os, se", "lo, la, los, las", "que, quien, lo que", "muy, bastante, demasiado"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Reflexive verbs take me/te/se/nos/os/se, matching the subject doing the action to itself."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:29859aa2', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Relative pronouns: que, quien, lo que", "reading": "<p><span data-say=\"que\">que</span> (who/that/which) is the most common relative pronoun and works for <strong>both</strong> people and things: <span data-say=\"El chico que vive aquí es mi amigo.\">El chico que vive aquí es mi amigo.</span></p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"quien\">quien</span> / quienes <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> means ‘who’ but is normally used only for people, especially after a preposition: <span data-say=\"la persona con quien hablo\">la persona con quien hablo</span> (the person I talk to).</p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"lo que\">lo que</span> <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> means ‘what / that which’ — it refers to an <strong>idea</strong>, not one specific noun: <span data-say=\"Hago lo que quiero.\">Hago lo que quiero.</span> (I do what I want.)</p>", "question": "Which relative pronoun means ‘what/that which’ and refers to an idea rather than one noun?", "options": ["lo que", "que", "quien", "quienes"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘lo que’ sums up a whole idea (‘what I want’), while ‘que’ and ‘quien(es)’ replace a specific noun."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:f3b9edba', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Negatives: nada, nunca, nadie, ni…ni", "reading": "<p>Spanish uses a <strong>double negative</strong> — ‘no’ plus a negative word: <span data-say=\"no veo nada\">no veo nada</span> (I don’t see anything/I see nothing).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...nada\">no … nada</span></td><td>nothing</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...nunca\">no … nunca</span> / <span data-say=\"jamás\">jamás</span></td><td>never</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...nadie\">no … nadie</span></td><td>nobody</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"no...ni...ni\">no … ni … ni</span></td><td>neither … nor</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Examples: <span data-say=\"no como nunca carne\">No como nunca carne.</span> (I never eat meat.) <span data-say=\"no hay nadie\">No hay nadie.</span> (There’s nobody.) <span data-say=\"no me gusta ni el fútbol ni el tenis\">No me gusta ni el fútbol ni el tenis.</span> (I like neither football nor tennis.)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> You can drop ‘no’ if the negative word comes BEFORE the verb: <span data-say=\"nunca voy al gimnasio\">Nunca voy al gimnasio.</span> (I never go to the gym.)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> <span data-say=\"nada\">nada</span> and <span data-say=\"nadie\">nadie</span> can also stand ALONE as pronouns, with no ‘no’ at all, when they come before the verb: <span data-say=\"Nada es imposible.\">Nada es imposible.</span> (Nothing is impossible.) <span data-say=\"Nadie lo sabe.\">Nadie lo sabe.</span> (Nobody knows it.)</p>", "question": "How do you say ‘I don’t see anything’ correctly in Spanish?", "options": ["No veo nada.", "No veo.", "Veo nada.", "No veo algo."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Spanish needs the double negative: no + veo + nada. Dropping ‘nada’, dropping ‘no’, or using ‘algo’ (something) are all wrong."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:ff3016a5', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Connectors and intensifiers", "reading": "<p>Basic connectors join ideas: <span data-say=\"y\">y</span> (and), <span data-say=\"pero\">pero</span> (but), <span data-say=\"porque\">porque</span> (because), <span data-say=\"también\">también</span> (also), <span data-say=\"además\">además</span> (furthermore).</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> For top marks add: <span data-say=\"sin embargo\">sin embargo</span> (however) and <span data-say=\"aunque\">aunque</span> (although) — <span data-say=\"aunque\">aunque</span> introduces a <strong>contrast</strong>, unlike ‘además’ which adds an idea.</p>\n            <p>Intensifiers strengthen or soften an adjective: <span data-say=\"muy\">muy</span> (very), <span data-say=\"bastante\">bastante</span> (quite), <span data-say=\"demasiado\">demasiado</span> (too much/many), <span data-say=\"un poco\">un poco</span> (a bit).</p>\n            <p>Example: <span data-say=\"Me gusta el deporte, pero prefiero la música. Además, toco la guitarra. Sin embargo, no tengo mucho tiempo.\">Me gusta el deporte, pero prefiero la música. Además, toco la guitarra. Sin embargo, no tengo mucho tiempo.</span></p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> <span data-say=\"sino\">sino</span> means \"but rather\" — use it instead of ‘pero’ after a negative when directly contrasting two things: <span data-say=\"No es rojo, sino azul.\">No es rojo, sino azul.</span> (It''s not red, but blue.)</p>", "question": "Which connector means ‘although’ and introduces a contrast?", "options": ["aunque", "porque", "también", "además"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘aunque’ (although) signals a contrast; ‘porque’ gives a reason, and ‘también’/‘además’ add extra ideas rather than contrast them."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:617da4e4', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Demonstratives: this/these, that/those, that (over there)", "reading": "<p>Demonstratives show distance from the speaker. Spanish has three \"distances\": close (<span data-say=\"este\">este/esta</span>, this), middle (<span data-say=\"ese\">ese/esa</span>, that), and far (<span data-say=\"aquel\">aquel/aquella</span>, that … over there).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"estos libros\">estos libros</span></td><td>these books (masc., close)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"estas casas\">estas casas</span></td><td>these houses (fem., close)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"esos zapatos\">esos zapatos</span></td><td>those shoes (masc., middle distance)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"esas camisetas\">esas camisetas</span></td><td>those T-shirts (fem., middle distance)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"aquel edificio\">aquel edificio</span></td><td>that building over there (masc.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"aquella montaña\">aquella montaña</span></td><td>that mountain over there (fem.)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"aquellos años\">aquellos años</span></td><td>those years (long ago/far, masc. pl.) <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span></td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"aquellas fotos\">aquellas fotos</span></td><td>those photos (far, fem. pl.) <span class=\"tier-h\">H</span></td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> When the word doesn''t point at one specific noun — just an idea or an unknown thing — Spanish uses the neuter forms <span data-say=\"esto\">esto</span> (this) and <span data-say=\"aquello\">aquello</span> (that): <span data-say=\"¿Qué es esto?\">¿Qué es esto?</span> (What is this?) <span data-say=\"Aquello que dijiste me sorprendió.\">Aquello que dijiste me sorprendió.</span> (That thing you said surprised me.)</p>", "question": "Which word means ‘this’ when you aren''t pointing at one specific noun, just an idea or unknown thing?", "options": ["esto", "estos", "estas", "aquellos"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘esto’ is the neuter form used for an idea or unknown thing; ‘estos/estas’ agree with a specific masc./fem. noun, and ‘aquellos’ means ‘those’ far away."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:4ffb1ff8', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "More prepositions: para, sin, hasta, desde", "reading": "<p><span data-say=\"para\">para</span> means \"for\" or \"in order to\" — it points to a purpose, destination or recipient: <span data-say=\"Estudio para aprender.\">Estudio para aprender.</span> (I study in order to learn.) <span data-say=\"Este regalo es para ti.\">Este regalo es para ti.</span> (This present is for you.)</p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"sin\">sin</span> means \"without\": <span data-say=\"sin duda\">sin duda</span> (without doubt), <span data-say=\"Salió sin comer.\">Salió sin comer.</span> (He/she left without eating.)</p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"hasta\">hasta</span> means \"until\", \"up to\" or \"even\": <span data-say=\"hasta luego\">hasta luego</span> (see you later), <span data-say=\"Trabajé hasta las diez.\">Trabajé hasta las diez.</span> (I worked until ten.)</p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"desde\">desde</span> means \"from\" or \"since\": <span data-say=\"Vivo aquí desde 2020.\">Vivo aquí desde 2020.</span> (I''ve lived here since 2020.) <span data-say=\"desde mi casa\">desde mi casa</span> (from my house).</p>", "question": "Which preposition means ‘since’ or ‘from’ (a point in time or place)?", "options": ["desde", "hasta", "sin", "para"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘desde’ = since/from a starting point; ‘hasta’ = until/up to an end point, ‘sin’ = without, and ‘para’ = for/in order to."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:96f5d7b9', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "otro, alguno, ninguno — another, some, none", "reading": "<p><span data-say=\"otro\">otro</span> / otra means \"another\" or \"other\" — unlike English, Spanish never puts ‘un/una’ before it: <span data-say=\"otro día\">otro día</span> (another day), NOT \"un otro día\".</p>\n            <p><span data-say=\"alguno\">alguno</span> shortens to <span data-say=\"algún\">algún</span> before a masculine singular noun: <span data-say=\"algún día\">algún día</span> (some day). As a pronoun it means \"someone/some (of them)\": <span data-say=\"¿Tienes alguna idea? Sí, tengo alguna.\">¿Tienes alguna idea? Sí, tengo alguna.</span> (Do you have an idea? Yes, I have one.)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> <span data-say=\"ninguno\">ninguno</span> shortens to <span data-say=\"ningún\">ningún</span> before a masculine singular noun and means \"no/not any\": <span data-say=\"No tengo ningún problema.\">No tengo ningún problema.</span> (I don''t have any problem.) As a pronoun: <span data-say=\"¿Tienes hermanos? No, no tengo ninguno.\">¿Tienes hermanos? No, no tengo ninguno.</span> (Do you have siblings? No, I don''t have any.)</p>", "question": "How do you say ‘I don''t have any problem’ correctly?", "options": ["No tengo ningún problema.", "No tengo otro problema.", "Tengo ningún problema.", "No tengo alguno problema."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘ningún’ shortens before a masc. singular noun and needs ‘no’ before the verb. Option C drops ‘no’, and option D wrongly keeps the full form ‘alguno’ instead of ‘ningún’, giving the wrong meaning too."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:6b7a2632', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Possessive pronouns: el mío, el tuyo, el suyo, el nuestro, el vuestro", "reading": "<p>Possessive pronouns replace \"mi coche\" with just \"mine\" — they agree with the noun they replace in gender and number, and usually take an article (el/la/los/las).</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"el mío\">el mío</span> / la mía</td><td>mine</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"el tuyo\">el tuyo</span> / la tuya</td><td>yours (tú)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"el suyo\">el suyo</span> / la suya</td><td>his / hers / theirs / yours (usted)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"el nuestro\">el nuestro</span> / la nuestra</td><td>ours</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"el vuestro\">el vuestro</span> / la vuestra</td><td>yours (vosotros)</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Examples: <span data-say=\"Tu casa es grande; la mía es pequeña.\">Tu casa es grande; la mía es pequeña.</span> (Your house is big; mine is small.) <span data-say=\"Vuestro coche es azul; el nuestro es rojo.\">Vuestro coche es azul; el nuestro es rojo.</span> (Your car is blue; ours is red.)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> Don''t confuse the possessive pronoun (<span data-say=\"el vuestro\">el vuestro</span> = yours) with the possessive determiner <span data-say=\"vuestro coche\">vuestro coche</span> (your car), which goes directly before the noun with no article.</p>", "question": "Which possessive pronoun means ‘mine’, replacing a feminine noun like ‘la casa’?", "options": ["la mía", "el mío", "la tuya", "la nuestra"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘la mía’ agrees with a feminine noun and means ‘mine’. ‘el mío’ is masculine, and ‘la tuya’/‘la nuestra’ mean ‘yours’/‘ours’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:dff5e7be', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "el que / el cual — advanced relative pronouns", "reading": "<p><span data-say=\"el que\">el que</span> / la que / los que / las que means \"the one(s) who/that\" — it refers back to a person or thing without repeating the noun: <span data-say=\"De todos los libros, el que más me gustó fue éste.\">De todos los libros, el que más me gustó fue éste.</span> (Of all the books, the one I liked most was this one.)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> <span data-say=\"el cual\">el cual</span> / la cual / los cuales / las cuales is a more formal version of \"que\", used especially straight after a preposition to avoid confusion: <span data-say=\"La empresa para la cual trabajo es española.\">La empresa para la cual trabajo es española.</span> (The company for which I work is Spanish.)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> <span data-say=\"los demás\">los demás</span> / las demás means \"the others\" or \"the rest\": <span data-say=\"Yo terminé, pero los demás todavía trabajan.\">Yo terminé, pero los demás todavía trabajan.</span> (I finished, but the others are still working.)</p>", "question": "What does ‘los demás’ mean in ‘Yo terminé, pero los demás todavía trabajan’?", "options": ["the others", "everyone, no exceptions", "none of them", "some of them"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘los demás’ = the others/the rest of the group, unlike ‘todos’ (everyone), ‘ninguno’ (none) or ‘algunos’ (some)."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:08ad3130', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Numbers: teens, tens, hundreds and thousands", "reading": "<p>Some higher numbers need extra care with spelling and gender agreement.</p>\n            <table class=\"vocab-tbl\">\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"doce\">doce</span></td><td>12 — twelve</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"diecisiete\">diecisiete</span></td><td>17 — seventeen</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"diecinueve\">diecinueve</span></td><td>19 — nineteen</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"veinte\">veinte</span></td><td>20 — twenty (veinti- before 21–29: veintiuno)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"sesenta\">sesenta</span></td><td>60 — sixty</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"setenta\">setenta</span></td><td>70 — seventy</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"ochenta\">ochenta</span></td><td>80 — eighty</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"cien, ciento\">cien / ciento</span></td><td>100 — cien alone/before a noun; ciento inside a bigger number (ciento cincuenta = 150)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"setecientos\">setecientos</span></td><td>700 — seven hundred (agrees: setecientas personas)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"novecientos\">novecientos</span></td><td>900 — nine hundred (agrees: novecientas personas)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"mil\">mil</span></td><td>1.000 — a thousand (never \"un mil\")</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><span data-say=\"millón\">millón</span></td><td>1.000.000 — a million (needs \"de\": un millón de euros)</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> Hundreds agree in gender with the noun: <span data-say=\"setecientas personas\">setecientas personas</span> (700 people, fem.) but <span data-say=\"setecientos euros\">setecientos euros</span> (700 euros, masc.).</p>", "question": "Which number word never takes ‘un’ in front of it, unlike English ‘a thousand’?", "options": ["mil", "millón", "ciento", "cien"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Spanish just says ‘mil’ (a/one thousand), never ‘un mil’. ‘millón’ DOES need ‘un’ (un millón), and ‘cien/ciento’ work differently again."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:learn:a544027d', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Question words and ‘with you’: cuánto, contigo", "reading": "<p><span data-say=\"¿cuánto?\">¿cuánto?</span> / ¿cuánta? / ¿cuántos? / ¿cuántas? means \"how much/how many\" and agrees with the noun: <span data-say=\"¿Cuánto cuesta?\">¿Cuánto cuesta?</span> (How much does it cost?) <span data-say=\"¿Cuántos hermanos tienes?\">¿Cuántos hermanos tienes?</span> (How many siblings do you have?)</p>\n            <p><span class=\"tier-h\">H</span> <span data-say=\"contigo\">contigo</span> is a special contraction of \"con + ti\" meaning \"with you\" (informal singular) — it doesn''t follow the usual \"con + pronoun\" pattern: <span data-say=\"¿Puedo ir contigo?\">¿Puedo ir contigo?</span> (Can I go with you?) The equivalent for \"with me\" is <span data-say=\"conmigo\">conmigo</span>.</p>", "question": "How do you say ‘Can I go with you?’ to a friend, using the special contraction for ‘con + ti’?", "options": ["¿Puedo ir contigo?", "¿Puedo ir con tigo?", "¿Puedo ir con tú?", "¿Puedo ir sin ti?"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘con + ti’ contracts irregularly to one word, ‘contigo’. Option B wrongly splits it into two words, option C uses the subject pronoun ‘tú’ instead of ‘ti’, and option D means ‘without you’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:8e87f87b', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Veo lo.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Lo veo.</p>", "question": "Why is ‘Veo lo’ wrong?", "options": ["the object pronoun must go BEFORE a conjugated verb (Lo veo)", "the pronoun ‘lo’ should be ‘la’ instead", "the verb ‘veo’ is spelt incorrectly", "object pronouns can never be used with a conjugated verb like ‘veo’, only with an infinitive such as ‘ver’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "With a conjugated verb the pronoun comes before it; it only attaches after an infinitive or gerund."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:12c80591', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Yo yo hablo español.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Hablo español.</p>", "question": "What’s wrong with doubling the pronoun in ‘Yo yo hablo’?", "options": ["the subject pronoun only needs using once, or can be dropped, since the verb ending shows ‘yo’", "‘yo’ must always be repeated twice in a row for extra emphasis in every single Spanish sentence you write", "‘hablo’ needs two subject pronouns to agree", "Spanish verbs cannot be used without two pronouns"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘Hablo’ already carries the meaning of ‘yo’; one pronoun (or none) is correct, never a double."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:080c5ceb', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> El libro quien compré es interesante.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> El libro que compré es interesante.</p>", "question": "Why is ‘el libro quien compré’ wrong?", "options": ["‘quien’ only refers to people, not things — things need ‘que’", "‘quien’ must always follow the word ‘lo’ before any noun or pronoun", "‘compré’ should be changed to ‘compro’", "‘libro’ needs a written accent on the final syllable"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘quien/quienes’ refers to people; a thing like ‘el libro’ needs ‘que’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:10581af0', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> No veo.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> No veo nada.</p>", "question": "Why is ‘No veo’ alone not correct for ‘I don’t see anything’?", "options": ["Spanish needs the double negative: no + veo + nada", "‘veo’ on its own already means ‘nothing’ without adding any other word", "‘no’ on its own already means ‘nothing’", "you should never use ‘no’ together with ‘ver’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Without ‘nada’, ‘No veo’ just means ‘I don’t see’ — it is missing what you don’t see."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:57128441', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Me gusta el deporte, aunque prefiero la música.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Me gusta el deporte, además prefiero la música.</p>", "question": "What’s the problem with ‘aunque’ here if you mean ‘as well as that’?", "options": ["‘aunque’ means ‘although’ and introduces a contrast, not an addition", "‘aunque’ is spelt incorrectly and should not appear anywhere in the sentence", "‘aunque’ can only be used to start a question", "‘aunque’ is one of the negative words like ‘nada’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘aunque’ signals a contrast (although); to ADD an idea you need ‘además’ or ‘también’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:misc:98500395', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Voy a leer un otro libro.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Voy a leer otro libro.</p>", "question": "Why is ‘un otro libro’ wrong?", "options": ["Spanish never puts ‘un/una’ before ‘otro’ — just ‘otro libro’", "‘otro’ must always come immediately after the noun it describes, never before it", "‘libro’ should be plural in this sentence", "‘un’ should be replaced with ‘el’ before ‘otro’"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘otro’ already means ‘another’, so it never takes ‘un/una’ in front — ‘otro libro’ is correct on its own."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tips:0f74e702', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Paper 1 — Listening: pronouns and negatives in context", "reading": "Listen for whether the object pronoun is ‘lo/la’ (singular) or ‘los/las’ (plural), and for the negative word right after ‘no’ — ‘nada’, ‘nunca’ or ‘nadie’ completely change the meaning even though they sound similar.", "question": "You hear ‘no … nadie’. What does that tell you?", "options": ["nobody is involved", "nothing at all happened", "the action never happens", "everything is fine"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘no … nadie’ = nobody, not ‘nada’ (nothing) or ‘nunca’ (never)."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tips:b6e036df', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Paper 3 — Reading: relative pronouns link ideas", "reading": "Long reading texts use ‘que’, ‘quien’ and ‘lo que’ to join sentences. Track WHO or WHAT each pronoun refers back to — that noun is usually a few words earlier in the sentence.", "question": "In ‘Hago lo que quiero’, what does ‘lo que’ refer to?", "options": ["a whole idea (‘what I want’), not one specific noun", "one masculine singular noun that was already mentioned earlier in the same sentence", "a person the speaker is talking to directly", "a place mentioned earlier in the text"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘lo que’ sums up an idea, unlike ‘que’, which replaces one specific noun."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:tips:1fdbccb2', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — Paper 4 — Writing: use connectors and pronouns for range", "reading": "Top-band answers combine a pronoun (‘lo/la’), a negative (‘nunca’, ‘nada’) and a Higher connector (‘sin embargo’, ‘aunque’) in the same paragraph, instead of repeating ‘y’ and ‘pero’ throughout.", "question": "Which answer shows the widest range of structures?", "options": ["Me gusta el fútbol, pero nunca lo juego porque, sin embargo, prefiero nadar", "Me gusta el fútbol y me gusta nadar y me gusta el baloncesto y también me gusta el tenis", "Me gusta el deporte", "No me gusta nada"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "It combines a pronoun (lo), a negative (nunca) and Higher connectors (pero, sin embargo) — range plus accuracy, not just repeated ‘y’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors:fib:6c6834f8', 'spanish', 'spanish:g-6-pronouns-negatives-and-connectors', 'G.6 Pronouns, Negatives and Connectors', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "¿Tienes el libro? Sí, _____ tengo. (it — masculine, direct object pronoun)", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["lo", "sesenta", "diecisiete", "nunca"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "lo"}}'::jsonb),
